<HEADLINE>
FT  23 SEP 94 / International Company News: General Motors in pact to sell
car rental offshoot
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DETROIT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
General Motors and Vestar Equity Partners have signed a letter of intent for
GM to sell the assets of National Car Rental System to an investment group
led by Vestar, Reuter reports from Detroit.
The proposed agreement includes provisions for National to continue to
employ its 6,400 employees, and to maintain its long-term fleet agreement
with GM to purchase vehicles.
In June, National's president Lawrence Ramaekers told Reuters the rental
firm was expected to fetch more than Dollars 1bn.
GM declined to comment on the sale price, saying the deal was contingent on
the signing of a definitive agreement and the approval of GM's directors.
The US carmaker said the sale reflected its strategy to divest non-core
assets. GM acquired 45 per cent of National in September 1988 and, since
then, has acquired full ownership of the company.
Last year, GM retained Jay Alix &amp; Associates, turnround specialists to
improve National's operating performance.
'National Car Rental is an established franchise that we believe has real
potential,' John Howard, co-chief executive of Vestar Equity Partners, said
in a statement. 'We have been quite impressed with the efforts of GM and Jay
Alix &amp; Associates to improve National's operating performance. We will work
closely with the management team to build on this progress.'
National services more than 5,000 locations in 132 countries worldwide.
New York-based Vestar has organised 13 management buy-outs during the last
six years. The firm manages a Dollars 260m equity fund dedicated to
management buy-outs.
GM's move marks the second time this month one of Detroit's Big Three car
companies has sold its stake in rental car firms.
Earlier this month, Chrysler sold its stake in Snappy Rent-A-car to a group
of investors led by Jackson Partners LP in New York. Chrysler still owns a
stake in Thrifty and Dollar Rent-A-Car. In April, Ford Motor increased its
stake in Hertz to 100 per cent.
