<HEADLINE>
FT  23 SEP 94 / International Company News: CP Rail offers CDollars 1.4bn
for rival network
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CP Rail System, the railway subsidiary of Montreal-based conglomerate
Canadian Pacific, has offered to pay CDollars 1.4bn (USDollars 1.04bn) for
the eastern Canadian operations of government-owned Canadian National,
Canada's other main railway.
The bid follows a recent pattern of mergers and acquisitions throughout the
North American rail industry as operators seek to expand their networks and
improve competitiveness by combining resources.
CP Rail and CN earlier this year discussed merging their eastern Canadian
operations, which cover their entire network east of Chicago and Winnipeg.
However, the two sides failed to agree on the value of their respective
assets.
Mr Barry Scott, CP Rail's chief executive, yesterday described the bid as 'a
singular opportunity for both the Canadian government and Canadian
taxpayers'. He noted that CP's offer would enable the government to
privatise half of Canada's biggest public corporation and would
substantially lower CN's debt.
Canadian Pacific said that the purchase would be financ-ed from existing
resources.
CP's offer will be an important test of the economic policies of the Liberal
government, which took office last October and has so far been lukewarm
towards privatisations following a wave of disposals by the former
Progressive Conservative government.
While business interests favour privatisation, the CP bid is likely to be
opposed by many other groups, ranging from trade unions to communities which
may be in danger of losing their rail service. CP said yesterday that it
would shut one of two lines serving the east coast port of Halifax, Nova
Scotia.
CP Rail said its offer would be open for 90 days. It urged the government to
speed up the process of obtaining the required regulatory approvals for
constructing rail connections and the eventual abandonment of surplus
assets, as well as determining appropriate bargaining units for labour
agreements.
The takeover would come into effect on January 1 1996. CP said it would aim
to cut the combined workforce of 16,500 people by about 2,500 over the first
four years.
