FT  23 SEP 94 / UK Company News: Towry Law advances to Pounds 2.82m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Towry Law, the independent financial advice chain which floated last
November, reported pre-tax profits up 16 per cent from Pounds 2.43m to
Pounds 2.82m, after listing costs of Pounds 237,000.
Mr Cecil Law, chairman, said: 'this has not been an easy year. Both our UK
financial planning and general insurance broking divisions are operating in
what are currently difficult markets, created by such factors as an
unsettled investment climate and rate softening in general insurance.'
The company has plans for a 'major cost management programme', which will
hit profitability in the first half of the year, and could involve some job
losses. It also plans to invest more in information technology, training and
compliance.
However, Mr Law said encouraging signs for the company included a 13 per
cent increase in new business, a 16 per cent rise to Pounds 6.2m for renewal
income and fees, and 34 per cent growth in income from international
financial planning.
Mr Alan Wesley, chief executive, said that although Towry Law did not expect
to have to pay any compensation as a result of the SIB enquiry into pension
transfers, it had made a 'substantial provision' for the extra cost of
temporary staff who might be needed to re-examine old files to comply with
SIB rulings.
Trading profits rose 26 per cent to Pounds 3.06m. Earnings per share grew 14
per cent to 11.6p (10.2p). A final dividend of 3p (1.8p) makes a total of
4.5p (3.6p) - a 25 per cent gain.
