<HEADLINE>
FT  23 SEP 94 / RMC buoyed by UK recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PRICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The continued strength of the German construction market, and a firm
recovery in the UK, helped RMC Group achieve a 60 per cent rise in
first-half pre-tax profits from Pounds 61.6m to Pounds 98.8m.
Turnover rose 14 per cent to Pounds 1.92bn (Pounds 1.69bn), with Germany
contributing Pounds 782.2m, an increase of Pounds 55.4m on the previous
year. Profits from German operations - where RMC has a dominating 16 per
cent share of the ready mixed cement market - grew 8 per cent from Pounds
52.9m to Pounds 57.2m.
UK profits more than doubled from Pounds 14.1m to Pounds 33.3m on turnover
16 per cent ahead at Pounds 527m (Pounds 454.3m). Mr Derek Jenkins, finance
director, said price increases of around 8 per cent in the UK concrete
business were being passed on to customers.
'We are simply recovering some of the ground lost during the recession and
getting back to something like adequate returns,' he said.
However he did not expect price rises to continue at the same rate during
the second half, although RMC would benefit from the 'plateauing' effect of
the new higher prices at the full-year.
RMC confirmed recent evidence from others in the construction industry of a
strong recovery in the UK's new house market, with the south-east in
particular seeing good demand.
Margins in eastern Germany remained firm and Mr Jenkins forecast
double-digit growth in volume terms for the foreseeable future. The
country's housing market was also maintaining solid expansion and RMC said
that fears that the market may peak would be offset by the beginning of a
pick-up in the commercial market. The transfer of the government from Bonn
to Berlin - close to RMC's German operations centre - would underpin this
growth, according to Mr Jenkins.
Turnover from RMC's other European operations rose 19 per cent to Pounds
421.6m (Pounds 353m) with profits 33 per cent higher at Pounds 16.4m (Pounds
12.1m). France was undergoing a 'gentle recovery', while Spain was beginning
to pick up after its recent slump.
Improved conditions in Israel and the US saw profits from the non-European
division jump 75 per cent to Pounds 10m (Pounds 5.7m) on turnover 24 per
cent ahead at Pounds 188.3m (Pounds 151.2m).
Earnings per share almost doubled from 13.4p to 24.6p. The interim dividend
rises from 6.6p to 7p.
Lex, Page 22
</TEXT>
