<HEADLINE>
FT  23 SEP 94 / Storm likely as former NHS chief executive joins Bupa
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE and IAN HOLDSWORTH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir Duncan Nichol, chief executive of the National Heath Service until
earlier this year, is to join the board of Bupa, the UK's largest private
healthcare organisation. The appointment is likely to cause political
controversy.
In July, Sir Duncan launched Healthcare 2000, a commission to investigate
the future of healthcare provision.
Critics of the government's effort to encourage greater private-sector
involvement in the NHS will regard the Bupa appointment as evidence of an
increasingly uncomfortable overlap between the two sectors.
Mr David Blunkett, shadow health secretary, said: 'This is the clearest
indication yet of the degree to which the government is blurring the
distinction between a public NHS and the private health sector.'
The appointment will also revive arguments over how soon after leaving
public office senior civil servants should be able to take up such posts.
The Department of Health would not comment last night on any possible
conflict of interest. Civil servants of Sir Duncan's rank must apply for
approval to take an a outside appointment if it is within two years of
leaving Whitehall. Sir Duncan's move had been handled with 'statutory
propriety', an official said.
Mr Tom Sackville, junior health minister, said: 'The appointment is a matter
for Bupa and for Sir Duncan. There is positive benefit to the NHS in close
co-operation with the private sector.'
Sir Duncan, 53, was appointed NHS chief executive in 1989 and held the post
until March this year. He was the first career NHS manager to head the
service, having started as a management trainee. Some colleagues will regard
his decision to join Bupa with surprise, since he was regarded as a staunch
supporter of the public health service.
Bupa has 46 per cent of the private healthcare market and the biggest number
of private hospitals, with 29 units and 1,785 beds.
</TEXT>
