<HEADLINE>
FT  23 SEP 94 / Supermarket fire risks cause increasing concern to insurers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The risk of fire in larger supermarkets is causing increasing concern among
insurers and safety experts following a spate of losses in recent months.
The lack of compartment walls, which would halt the spread of fire, and the
absence of sprinkler systems and roof venting in many stores have been
singled out as potential hazards.
The risks were highlighted at a conference this week organised by the Fire
Protection Association, a body linked to the insurance industry.
Recent losses include a supermarket fire in Hull in June, which caused
Pounds 10m property damage, and a blaze at a superstore in Chichester last
December, where damage amounted to Pounds 11m. The association reports nine
total losses over the last two years. Mr Stewart Kidd, a director of the
association, said recent incidents showed stores to be at 'considerable risk
from fire, no matter how it is caused'.
Mr Tony Baker, deputy director-general of the Association of British
Insurers, said: 'It is a real worry. Fires can spread very quickly from one
corner to the whole building.' The association has been in touch with the
Home Office and is pressing for tougher regulations, including compulsory
installation of sprinklers.
'The cost of installing sprinklers in large retail outlets is the same as
that of laying carpet,' Mr Kidd added.
Retailers insisted yesterday that fears were overplayed. 'We are constantly
being attacked on grounds of fire safety. It is an assertion which is not
borne out by the facts,' said Mr Mark Bradshaw, assistant director of the
British Retail Consortium, which represents about 90 per cent of the retail
industry.
Mr Bradshaw said supermarket owners fully complied with the statutory
framework and that criticisms exaggerated the effectiveness of sprinkler
systems.
'The basic concept that fire sprinklers are an all-round solution to our
problems is absolutely wrong,' he said. In a false alarm, sprinklers could
damage stock and building structures.
Instead, supermarket operators and other retailers placed more emphasis on
evacuation procedures, so that employees and customers could escape quickly.
He added: 'The assertion that sub-standard buildings are being constructed
is absolutely absurd. You have to pass very stringent building controls
which are tightly enforced by local and fire authorities.'
</TEXT>
