<HEADLINE>
FT  23 SEP 94 / Fiat chief calls for reforms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD GOURLAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Giovanni Agnelli, chairman of Fiat, Italy's biggest private-sector
industrial group, called in London yesterday for the reform of the Italian
public sector and welfare state.
Italy's public-sector debt was an obstacle to investment and economic
recovery, Mr Agnelli said at a ceremony to announce the UK's 1994 Venturer
of the Year award.
Italy's public-sector deficit has risen to more than 10 per cent of GDP and
the stock of debt is more than 120 per cent of GDP, considerably higher than
in the rest of Europe.
Mr Agnelli said Italy's economy was moving in the right direction, with
inflation falling, the balance of trade positive and competitiveness
improving but the situation in the Italian public sector and welfare state
was 'particularly grave'.
The Venturer of the Year award, sponsored by Cartier, the jewellers, The
Financial Times and the British Venture Capital Association, was won by Mr
Stephen Noar, a 47-year old dentist who eight years ago formed Denplan, a
company which provides private dental healthcare programmes.
He sold the company last year for Pounds 42m to Private Patients Plan, the
medical insurer.
