<HEADLINE>
FT  23 SEP 94 / Semtex found at IRA breakout jail: Anglo-Irish talks today
under fresh pressure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Police yesterday discovered three detonators and just over a pound of Semtex
explosive at the prison in Cambridgeshire at which five IRA terrorists
attempted an armed breakout this month.
The discovery - which puts Mr Michael Howard, the home secretary, under new
pressure and strains the Northern Ireland peace process - came on the eve of
the first Anglo-Irish intergovernmental conference since last month's IRA
ceasefire.
Mr Howard last night described the find - inside Whitemoor prison's
perimeter wall but outside its special secure unit - as a 'very very grave'
matter. The find will cast a shadow over the future of Mr Derek Lewis,
prison service director-general.
Since the breakout the six high-security prisons in Britain have been
undergoing intensive searches by tracker dogs for explosives and guns.
Sir Patrick Mayhew, Northern Ireland secretary, and Mr Dick Spring, the
Irish foreign minister, are expected to use today's meeting in London to
take stock of the situation in Ulster in the light of recent developments.
Mr Spring will have his first meeting with Mr Tony Blair, Labour leader, at
breakfast today.
Dublin is keen for discussions to cover the sensitive subject of north-south
economic co-operation and general prospects for the province's economy.
The government said last night that six more roads on the Irish border were
to be reopened, bringing the total to 16.
Mr Major, speaking in South Africa yesterday, ruled out an amnesty for
convicted terrorists. Circumstances in Northern Ireland were 'not remotely
similar' to those in South Africa, where some prisoners convicted of
offences committed before the first all-race elections in April have been
released.
Sir Patrick and Mr Spring will review progress on the framework document
which they hope will inject momentum into political talks involving the main
political parties in the province.
With significant differences understood to remain between the two sides on
important constitutional issues, it seems increasingly likely that the
framework document will not be published until at least November.
Preliminary talks between London and Sinn Fein, to which the government is
committed within three months of a permanent end to IRA violence, could
start before it appears.
Prominent nationalists are said to be keen that round-table talks involving
the parties should not resume until Sinn Fein is able to take part.
But the longer the document is delayed, the longer the province may have to
wait for an end to loyalist violence.
Yesterday's Semtex discovery brought sharp political reaction. Mr John
Prescott, Labour's deputy leader, questioned Mr Howard's competence. He
said: 'I hope the prime minister will have him in to talk about what is
going on in our prisons.'
Mr Alan Beith, Liberal Democrat home affairs spokesman, said: 'Mr Howard
must stop escaping full responsibility for the state of the prisons and make
sure the resources are there to carry out the searches which are needed.'
Initial reaction from unionists was restrained. Mr John Taylor, MP for
Strangford, said he did not think it would pose a problem for the ceasefire.
</TEXT>
