<HEADLINE>
FT  23 SEP 94 / Ministers determined to sell Post Office stake
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD and ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, and Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and
industry secretary, yesterday underlined their determination to press ahead
with partial privatisation of the Post Office.
At an informal meeting of the cabinet's committee on industrial, commercial
and consumer affairs, the ministers voiced their support for a majority sale
of the Royal Mail.
They are understood to enjoy the support of Mr Douglas Hurd, the foreign
secretary, but Mr John Major, the prime minister, is still wary about the
potential political cost of a decision that Labour says will damage rural
post offices.
A final decision will be deferred until the conclusion of the consultation
period at the end of this month.
The meeting came as Mr Richard Dykes, managing director of Post Office
Counters, said yesterday that investment in advanced technology in village
post offices should put an end to rumours that partial privatisation would
lead to closures.
The Post Office said bids would close today for the first stages of a Pounds
100m plan to automate the UK's 20,000 post offices. The project, announced
in May, will place a computer terminal on each post office counter, making
it simpler to pay benefits.
The smallest rural post office will then have access to information and
services such as international cash transfer and travel insurance. The
system should make social security fraud more difficult.
</TEXT>
