<HEADLINE>
FT  23 SEP 94 / Inflation 'toughest on the rich' under Tories
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Richer households have suffered a rate of inflation some 3 percentage points
higher than the official inflation rate under the Conservative government,
an economic study says.
In contrast, the rate of inflation experienced by the poorest 10 per cent of
the population was about 1 percentage point lower than the officially
defined measures.
The research, carried out by the Institute of Fiscal Studies and sponsored
by the Joseph Rowntree Foundation, shows that between 1979 and 1992 the rate
of inflation experienced by households has varied significantly from the
official inflation data shown in the retail prices index.
The report admits that the retail prices index is not an entirely accurate
measurement of inflation because of the differing impact of housing costs.
If capital gains and losses on housing are included, for example, the data
suggests that elderly poor people who own their houses may have been
disproportionately hit.
Nevertheless the findings are likely to prove controversial, not least
because they run contrary to the usual wisdom that poor households have
suffered under Conservative rule.
The main reason for the discrepancy, the report says, lies in the differing
patterns of consumption of rich and poor households. Rich households, the
report notes, spend a large proportion of their budgets on luxury items,
with two-thirds of their income spent on items that have been subject to
value added tax.
Poor households, by contrast, spend more on basic necessities such as food,
fuel and clothing, with only a third of their income spent on items subject
to VAT.
Because the cost of luxuries has risen faster than overall inflation, not
least because of the rise in VAT on luxury items, this has meant that richer
households have been disproportionately affected. Poorer households, by
contrast, have benefited from the fact that the relative cost of food,
clothing and fuel has fallen during this period.
UK Household Cost-of-Living Indices: 1979-1992. Institute of Fiscal Studies,
7 Ridgemount St, London, WC1E 7AE. Pounds 6.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
