<HEADLINE>
FT  23 SEP 94 / Private cash plan for Scots M-way
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government's intended method of financing road construction with private
funds is set to make its Scottish debut. Ministers hope to use the method to
complete the M74 motorway in southern Scotland, and could eventually
transfer 100km (62 miles) of new motorway to a private operator.
Mr Ian Lang, Scottish secretary, said the Scottish Office was exploring the
possibility of using the private-finance route for two remaining sections of
the M74 project, on which work has not yet begun. He said the Scottish
Office was talking to the Department of Transport about applying the same
solution to an English stretch of the A74 between Carlisle and the border at
Gretna.
Under the design, build, finance and operate method, the contractor finances
the construction of the road and maintains it for 15 to 25 years, recouping
money from the exchequer through 'shadow tolls' based on the amount of
traffic using the road.
Last month Mr John Watts, roads minister for England and Wales, asked
contractors to bid for the first four such road schemes in England.
The Scottish Office envisages that a contractor which undertook to complete
the M74 in Scotland and England would then take over the full 100km from
Abington to Carlisle and operate it. To complete the three stretches would
cost about Pounds 160m.
Mr Lang was opening an 18.6km stretch of the M74 between Dinwoodie Green and
Ecclefechan in Dumfries and Galloway.
The four sections have been completed for Pounds 100m by Miller Civil
Engineering and Balfour Beatty.
Two further sections under construction will be finished towards the end of
this year, meaning that more than two-thirds of the project will have been
completed at a total cost of nearly Pounds 350m.
Editorial comment, Page 21
</TEXT>
