<HEADLINE>
FT  23 SEP 94 / Major ends row with Thatcher on South Africa
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PRETORIA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A long-distance row between Mr John Major and Baroness Thatcher over the
economic prospects for South Africa is over, the prime minister said
yesterday.
The row blew up after Lady Thatcher told businessmen in Bombay that foreign
capital was unlikely to flow to South Africa because of concerns about
violence.
Her comments - which cast a shadow over Mr Major's three-day official visit
to South Africa - irritated the prime minister's party because they directly
contradicted his repeated declarations of confidence in the ability of the
government of national unity to achieve prosperity.
Mr Major welcomed a clarification of Lady Thatcher's remarks - issued by her
office in London after worried British officials pointed out the potential
diplomatic damage.
The statement, which expressed support for the South African government and
confidence in the country's economic future, 'answers the point thoroughly',
Mr Major said before leaving for London.
He said Lady Thatcher had encouraged investment in South Africa and
assistance for impoverished black townships throughout her 11 years as prime
minister, which ended in 1990.
'That she wishes South Africa well, and has done so continuously, I don't
think there is a shred of doubt,' he said.
Mr Major's successful South African trip, which also took in short visits to
Saudi Arabia and Abu Dhabi, has reinforced the growing confidence among his
advisers that the government's worst problems are over. Asked at a press
conference whether the government's fortunes had reached a turning point,
the prime minister responded cautiously: 'No wise politician ever says
that.'
But he is clearly hopeful that the government's popularity will be revived
by recent improvements in economic indicators, combined with progress
towards peace in Northern Ireland and the unofficial truce between the prime
minister and the Tory right.
'There are a series of things we have been doing for the last four years
which are now beginning to come together,' he said. 'People are beginning to
see the fruits.'
</TEXT>
