<HEADLINE>
FT  23 SEP 94 / Output growth may weaken, CBI forecasts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
One of the first hints that the recent strong growth in UK manufacturing
output might be levelling off emerged yesterday in a Confederation of
British Industry survey.
The survey, which covers about half of UK manufacturing employment and
exports, showed that the proportion of companies which expect output to
increase in the next four months fell in September.
Thirty four per cent of companies questioned said they expected output to
rise, while 11 per cent expected it to decline. The positive balance of 23
per cent was lower than in August's survey, when the positive balance was 30
per cent.
The CBI said yesterday that August's balance was the highest figure for six
years, and noted that this month's balance was still higher than last
September's balance of 17 per cent, and on a par with figures seen earlier
this year.
But the hints that the recent surge in activity might be levelling off are
unlikely to surprise the City, where many economists have been predicting
that output growth would ease slightly towards the end of this year.
The CBI said yesterday that more than 90 per cent of the survey was
conducted before the latest interest rate rise.
Some industry groups have warned that a rise in interest rates may damp
economic growth further.
Mr Eddie George, governor of the Bank of England, yesterday sought to rebut
these charges by insisting that a rate rise at this stage of the recovery
seemed just as likely to encourage business confidence in the sustainability
of the expansion and to encourage business investment as to damp them.
He told a CBI dinner in Gateshead: 'It was too much to hope that the
business community would actually welcome the move. By acting sooner rather
than later we can keep the economy growing at a sustainable pace and avoid
the need to bring it eventually to a grinding halt.'
Meanwhile, in a trend that will provide some boost to the government's fight
against inflation, the CBI survey showed that there was no increase in the
proportion of companies expecting to increase prices.
The proportion of companies which expect to increase prices in the next four
months, compared with those which expect to reduce them, was a positive
balance of 15 per cent, the same as in August, with two-thirds of companies
expecting no price change.
The survey showed that the proportion of companies reporting total order
books and export order books above normal was unchanged on the month,
suggesting that demand is stabilising. Meanwhile 17 per cent of companies
said that stocks were more than adequate, compared with 6 per cent which
said that they were less than adequate.
</TEXT>
