<HEADLINE>
FT  23 SEP 94 / World Trade News: UK-Greek team in tunnel deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KERIN HOPE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ATHENS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A British-Greek joint venture, Christiani &amp; Nielsen-TEGK, has signed an
Ecu40.2m (Dollars 50m) contract to build an undersea tunnel linking two
ports in western Greece.
The tunnel project, which is still to be ratified by parliament, is the
first infrastructure project to be launched under the European Union's new
Ecu16.8bn funding package for Greece.
Christiani &amp; Nielsen-TEGK was the low bidder among 10 consortia shortlisted
for the project, the environment and public works ministry said.
The 1km tunnel between Aktion and Preveza at the entrance to the Ambracian
Gulf will be constructed using a 'cut-and-cover' method. Several pre-cast
concrete segments will be sunk into a channel to be dredged in the seabed.
The choice of a tunnel rather than a bridge to replace a ferry crossing
between the two ports was made on environmental grounds to protect the gulf
and the site of a famous ancient naval battle in 31 BC, at which the Roman
fleet defeated Antony and Cleopatra, according to the environment and public
works ministry.
The tunnel link, due to be completed in 1998, is part of an EU-funded plan
to improve the road network and expand harbours in western Greece.
</TEXT>
