<HEADLINE>
FT  23 SEP 94 / British and US jets strike at Bosnian Serbs: Nato hits back
after attacks on UN troops
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRUCE CLARK and BERNARD GRAY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
British and US jets attacked a Bosnian Serb tank west of Sarajevo yesterday
after United Nations peacekeeping troops twice came under Serbian fire.
It was the fourth Nato attack on Bosnian Serb positions since UN troops were
deployed and reflected international exasperation with violations of a
weapons-free zone around the Bosnian capital.
The Nato retaliation was led by a US A-10 jet which strafed the Serbian tank
and was followed by two British Jaguars which dropped bombs on the position,
Nato officials said. Mr Warren Christopher, US secretary of state, warned in
Washington of more Nato air strikes if Bosnian Serbs violated exclusion
zones or attacked UN peacekeepers. But the Bosnian Serb army denounced the
air strike and said it reserved the right to attack Nato and UN
peacekeepers.
Earlier, a French armoured personnel carrier was hit by Bosnian Serb forces
as it monitored an exchange of fire between Bosnian Serb and Moslem-led
Bosnian forces near Sarajevo. One UN soldier was injured.
General Sir Michael Rose, the commander of UN peacekeeping forces in Bosnia,
defended the Nato action, saying the Serb attack on the French armoured
vehicle had been deliberate.
Gen Rose said the Serbs had one tank left in the weapons exclusion zone
around Sarajevo and that was chosen as the target. In his view, the strike
was a proportionate reaction to the Bosnian Serb attacks.
The air strike is the latest sign that the allies are taking a firmer stance
towards former Yugoslavia. Nato, urged on by the US, has been pressing hard
in recent days for a more vigorous effort to counter the Bosnian Serbs, who
have rejected an international peace plan.
The US administration has promised the powerful pro-Bosnian lobby in
Congress that it will start moves to lift the UN arms embargo against Bosnia
unless the Serbs accept the peace plan by October 15. European governments
have warned the US that that might lead to a disastrous escalation of
fighting.
The White House, which disclosed news of yesterday's air raid, has been
pressing for tougher enforcement of existing policies in Bosnia. General
Bertrand de Lapresle, commander of UN forces in former Yugoslavia, said the
air strike was a 'proportionate' reaction to the Serb attack.
Senior Nato officials have asked the UN for a stricter interpretation of the
rules under which heavy weapons in Sarajevo and the enclave of Gorazde - and
any forces that attack the UN anywhere in Bosnia - are subject to air
strikes.
UN commanders say they are better judges than Nato of when air strikes are
appropriate. However, yesterday's action seemed to have the full support of
both international organisations.
</TEXT>
